<!-- Frameless vs framed -->
<section class="en-section">
  <div class="en-container">
    <h2>Frameless vs Framed Enclosures: Before and After</h2>
    <p>The difference between a frameless glass curtain and a traditional aluminium-framed enclosure is dramatic — both visually and functionally. A framed enclosure creates a permanent room: once closed, you cannot open it fully. The aluminium profiles are always visible, breaking up your view and giving the terrace a "boxed-in" feel.</p>
    <p>A frameless glass curtain, by contrast, is completely reversible. Open it fully on a warm morning and your terrace becomes an extension of the outdoor garden. Close it on a cold evening and it instantly becomes a comfortable, wind-protected room. There are no vertical profiles to block the view — the glass panels sit edge-to-edge, creating a near-invisible barrier.</p>
    <p>From a planning perspective, frameless systems are also treated more favourably by communities and local councils. Because they have a lighter visual impact on the building's façade, they are less likely to require formal planning permission and more likely to sail through a community vote.</p>
    <p>After installation, the lifestyle benefits are immediately apparent. Homeowners across the Costa del Sol consistently report using their terraces for 8 to 10 additional months per year after installing glass curtains — compared with perhaps 4 or 5 months with an open terrace subject to wind and rain.</p>

